2.2 Hardware Specifications & Electrode Innovation (RGOPU)

A fundamental bottleneck in long-term, real-world EEG is electrode technology. v4.0 transitions from high-impedance multi-pin dry electrodes to RGOPU (Reduced Graphene Oxide / Polyurethane) semi-dry electrodes.

· Electrode Impedance & Stability: The RGOPU electrode achieves a skin-contact impedance of less than 5.6 kΩ at 10 Hz, which is equivalent to gold-standard wet electrodes and an order of magnitude lower than conventional dry electrodes (which range from 65–500 kΩ). Critically, this low impedance is maintained with high stability (potential drift of only ±2.22 μV/s) for over four hours, requiring only a small pre-charge of saline.
· Signal Fidelity: The signal quality is validated by a correlation coefficient of r = 0.960 ± 0.021 with wet Ag/AgCl electrodes, ensuring that the acquired signals are of research-grade quality without the need for abrasive skin preparation or conductive gels. The Randles equivalent circuit model confirms the reduced thermal noise floor (V_noise ≈ 0.064 µV RMS), which is well below the intrinsic noise of the ADS1299 analog front-end (~1 µVpp).

2.3 Predictive Contact Quality Index (CQI)

To ensure continuous signal fidelity, we implement a Predictive CQI algorithm on the STM32H743 microcontroller.

· Multi-Component Monitoring: Unlike a simple impedance check, the CQI integrates three metrics computed at 1 Hz: (1) 50/60 Hz noise proxy, (2) short-term vs. long-term signal variance stability, and (3) baseline drift rate.
· Proactive User Feedback: A linear trend extrapolation model predicts the time-to-failure for any degrading channel. The system issues a preemptive warning (e.g., "Channel Cz degrading—re-press electrode in 2 minutes") if the predicted CQI falls below the critical threshold (θ_bad = 0.4) within 120 seconds. This transforms reactive troubleshooting into proactive signal maintenance.

2.4 Embedded Compute & Thermal Management

The core processing is offloaded to an NVIDIA Jetson AGX Orin. The system is configured for a nominal 30W power mode (CPU: 8x 2.2 GHz, GPU: 1.1 GHz), balancing performance and thermal stability. A thermal-aware scheduler dynamically adjusts the power mode based on on-die temperature sensors (tegrastats), switching to a 15W fallback mode at 75°C to guarantee latency budgets and prevent thermal throttling. The unconstrained MAXN mode is explicitly excluded due to its instability under sustained loads.

3. Mathematical Foundations and Preprocessing

Robust decoding requires rigorous mathematical preprocessing. Our pipeline is built on Riemannian geometry and robust statistics.

3.1 Signal Model & Euclidean Alignment (EA)

The EEG data for trial i, X_i ∈ ℝ^{N_c × T}, is modeled as X_i(t) = A·S_i(t) + N(t). To mitigate inter-session and inter-subject variability, we apply Euclidean Alignment (EA). Given a reference covariance matrix R̄ = (1/M) Σ X_i X_i^T / (T-1), the aligned trial is X̃_i = R̄^{-1/2} X_i. This transformation centers the data, ensuring the mean covariance of aligned trials is the identity matrix, I. This is mathematically proven as:

(1/M) Σ X̃_i X̃_i^T / (T-1) = R̄^{-1/2} R̄ R̄^{-1/2} = I.

3.2 Riemannian Feature Extraction with Ledoit-Wolf Shrinkage

Features are extracted from the manifold of Symmetric Positive Definite (SPD) matrices, denoted S++_n.

· Robust Covariance Estimation: To avoid ill-conditioned covariance matrices, we employ the Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage estimator, which provides an analytically determined regularization to the sample covariance matrix C.
· Riemannian Re-centering: We compute the geometric mean (Fréchet mean) C̄ of the training set covariance matrices on S++_n. The convergence of the Karcher flow algorithm is guaranteed because the SPD manifold is a Cartan-Hadamard manifold (complete, simply connected, and with non-positive curvature).
· Tangent Space Projection: Each trial's covariance matrix is projected onto the tangent space at the mean using the logarithmic map: Si = Log{C̄}(C_i). The vectorized upper triangular part of this symmetric matrix, vech(**S**_i), forms our feature vector (x_feat ∈ ℝ^{528}).

4. Core Decoding Algorithms and Robustness Enhancements

The core of NeuroSync is its intelligent and robust decoding pipeline.

4.1 TCFormer Intent Decoder: A SOTA Benchmark

We utilize TCFormer, a temporal convolutional Transformer designed for EEG-based motor imagery decoding.

· Architecture: TCFormer integrates a Multi-Kernel CNN (MK-CNN) for spatial-temporal feature extraction, a Transformer encoder enhanced with Grouped Query Attention (GQA) and Rotary Positional Embedding (RoPE) for global context, and a Temporal Convolutional Network (TCN) head for long-range temporal modeling.
· Performance: On standard benchmarks, TCFormer achieves state-of-the-art subject-dependent accuracies of 84.79% on BCIC IV-2a, 87.71% on BCIC IV-2b, and 96.27% on HGD, outperforming previous CNN and standard Transformer models. This establishes a robust and verifiable performance baseline for our decoder.

4.2 Calibration-Free BCI with KD-CORAL

To eliminate the need for per-user calibration, we implement a Knowledge Distillation with Correlation Alignment (KD-CORAL) framework for domain generalization.

· Knowledge Distillation (KD): A subject-specific teacher network is trained for each source subject. A shared TCFormer student network is then trained to match the teacher's soft labels, thereby learning subject-invariant features.
· Correlation Alignment (CORAL): The CORAL loss explicitly minimizes the difference in second-order statistics (covariance matrices) of the features extracted from different source subjects. This aligns the feature distributions across subjects, a known technique for improving cross-subject performance. This approach targets zero-shot cross-subject accuracy of 70-75% on unseen users, without any calibration data.

4.3 Adversarial Robustness via ABAT

BCI decoders are known to be highly vulnerable to adversarial attacks. To secure the system, we employ Alignment-Based Adversarial Training (ABAT).

· Method: ABAT applies Euclidean Alignment before adversarial training with Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) attacks. By aligning the data distributions first, the PGD attacks become consistent across subjects and sessions. This synergy simultaneously improves the model's robustness to adversarial examples while maintaining or even increasing its accuracy on clean data, overcoming the traditional accuracy-robustness trade-off.
· Impact: v4.0 targets a post-ABAT clean accuracy of ≥ 84.79% and a PGD-10 adversarial accuracy of ≥ 60% (compared to an undefended baseline of ~20%).

5. Multimodal Fusion and Safety Mechanisms

The integration of multiple physiological signals and a robust safety channel are critical for reliable robotic control.

5.1 fNIRS Artifact Correction with WCBSI

v4.0 replaces a hard motion-gating approach for fNIRS with the Wavelet and Correlation-Based Signal Improvement (WCBSI) pipeline.

· Algorithm: WCBSI uses (1) wavelet coefficient kurtosis to detect motion artifacts, (2) a combination of cubic spline interpolation and wavelet thresholding for correction, and (3) Correlation-Based Signal Improvement (CBSI) to enforce the neurophysiological negative correlation between HbO and HbR signals.
· Performance: This hybrid correction approach has been shown to achieve a channel improvement rate of approximately 94.1%, significantly recovering usable hemodynamic data that would otherwise be discarded and enabling a more continuous cognitive load estimate.

5.2 Balanced Multimodal Learning with Dual-Decoder GradReb

Fusing fast, high-bandwidth EEG with slow, low-bandwidth fNIRS often leads to the EEG dominating the learning process. We address this with a Dual-Decoder architecture and Gradient Rebalancing (GradReb).

· Dual-Decoder: A Query Decoder (Cross-Attention) decouples intermodal coupling features, while separate branches learn modality-specific EEG and fNIRS representations.
· GradReb: During training, the gradient norms from the EEG and fNIRS branches are monitored. GradReb adaptively rescales the gradients to ensure that the maximum ratio between their magnitudes does not exceed a threshold (e.g., γ_max = 5.0). This prevents the EEG from overpowering the fNIRS branch, ensuring a balanced and more effective multimodal fusion.

5.3 Safety via ErrP Detection and Dual-Threshold Logic

An independent, parallel safety stream monitors for error-related potentials (ErrPs).

· EEG-Inception Model: We use the lightweight EEG-Inception CNN, the first model to integrate Inception modules for ERP detection, known for its high accuracy and low calibration requirements.
· Dual-Threshold State Machine: The continuous ErrP probability p_ErrP(t) triggers a two-stage response. A Soft Abort (θ_soft = 0.55) reduces robot velocity to 20% and issues a warning. A Hard Abort (θ_hard = 0.75) immediately freezes all joints and engages electromagnetic brakes. This mimics a natural, two-stage human reaction and prevents jarring emergency stops.
· Validation: The performance targets for the ErrP detector are a True Positive Rate (TPR) ≥ 70% and a True Negative Rate (TNR) ≥ 85%, which are consistent with the state-of-the-art in online asynchronous ErrP decoding.

6. Intelligent Autonomy: The Bayesian Goal-Inference Copilot

The highest-level control is governed by a proactive Bayesian goal-inference copilot.

6.1 From Reactive Blending to Proactive Inference

Unlike a reactive blending function ρ(t) that adjusts autonomy based on current state, our copilot maintains a belief distribution b(t) = P(goal = g_m | observations) over a discrete set of possible task goals G detected by an object detector.

6.2 Bayesian Belief Update and Control

At each time step, the belief is updated using a recursive Bayes filter with a Gaussian likelihood model based on the angle between the current arm trajectory and each goal g_m. Once the confidence in a goal exceeds a threshold (e.g., b_m > 0.70), the AI command u_AI(t) is conditioned on that goal, providing proactive assistance to complete the task. This approach is validated by recent research demonstrating that AI copilots using shared autonomy can enable users to achieve a 3.9-times-higher performance in target hit rate during cursor control and to perform robotic arm tasks that would be otherwise impossible.

6.3 End-to-End Latency and Computational Budget

