A.2 Karcher Flow Convergence on the SPD Manifold

Theorem A.2 (Uniqueness of the Fréchet Mean on \mathcal{S}_{++}^n). The manifold of n \times n Symmetric Positive Definite (SPD) matrices, denoted \mathcal{S}_{++}^n, equipped with the Affine-Invariant Riemannian metric, is a Cartan-Hadamard manifold (i.e., complete, simply connected, and with non-positive sectional curvature). Consequently, the Fréchet mean of a set of SPD matrices is unique.

Proof Sketch. The exponential map at any point is a global diffeomorphism (no cut locus), and the squared Riemannian distance function d^2(\mathbf{C}, \mathbf{C}_i) is strictly convex along geodesics due to non-positive curvature (see [1] for a complete proof). This strict convexity guarantees a unique global minimizer of the sum of squared distances, which is the Fréchet mean. \square

Corollary A.2.1 (Convergence of Karcher Flow). The iterative algorithm (Karcher flow) defined by:

\bar{\mathbf{C}}^{(k+1)} = \bar{\mathbf{C}}^{(k)} \exp\left( \frac{\alpha}{M} \sum_{i=1}^{M} \log\left( (\bar{\mathbf{C}}^{(k)})^{-1/2} \mathbf{C}_i (\bar{\mathbf{C}}^{(k)})^{-1/2} \right) \right)

with step size \alpha \in (0, 1], converges to the unique Fréchet mean of \{\mathbf{C}_i\}_{i=1}^{M} from any initial point in \mathcal{S}_{++}^n.

