A.3 Rotary Positional Embedding (RoPE) Relative Position Proof

RoPE encodes positional information by applying a rotation matrix to the query and key vectors. For a head of dimension d, the rotation matrix for position m is a block-diagonal matrix:

\mathbf{R}_m = \text{diag}(\mathbf{R}_m^{(1)}, \dots, \mathbf{R}_m^{(d/2)}), \quad \mathbf{R}_m^{(j)} = \begin{pmatrix} \cos(m\theta_j) & -\sin(m\theta_j) \\ \sin(m\theta_j) & \cos(m\theta_j) \end{pmatrix}

where \theta_j = 10000^{-2(j-1)/d}.

Theorem A.3 (Relative Position Property). The inner product between a rotated query at position m and a rotated key at position n depends only on the relative position (n-m):

\langle \mathbf{R}_m \mathbf{q}_m, \mathbf{R}_n \mathbf{k}_n \rangle = \mathbf{q}_m^\top \mathbf{R}_{n-m} \mathbf{k}_n

Proof. For any block j, the rotation matrices commute (being 2D rotations) and satisfy \mathbf{R}_m^{(j) \top} = \mathbf{R}_{-m}^{(j)}. Thus:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{R}_m^{(j) \top} \mathbf{R}_n^{(j)} &= \mathbf{R}_{-m}^{(j)} \mathbf{R}_n^{(j)} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} \cos(-m\theta_j) & -\sin(-m\theta_j) \\ \sin(-m\theta_j) & \cos(-m\theta_j) \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} \cos(n\theta_j) & -\sin(n\theta_j) \\ \sin(n\theta_j) & \cos(n\theta_j) \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} \cos((n-m)\theta_j) & -\sin((n-m)\theta_j) \\ \sin((n-m)\theta_j) & \cos((n-m)\theta_j) \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \mathbf{R}_{n-m}^{(j)}
\end{aligned}

Since this holds for all blocks j, we have \mathbf{R}_m^\top \mathbf{R}_n = \mathbf{R}_{n-m}. Therefore:

\langle \mathbf{R}_m \mathbf{q}_m, \mathbf{R}_n \mathbf{k}_n \rangle = (\mathbf{R}_m \mathbf{q}_m)^\top (\mathbf{R}_n \mathbf{k}_n) = \mathbf{q}_m^\top (\mathbf{R}_m^\top \mathbf{R}_n) \mathbf{k}_n = \mathbf{q}_m^\top \mathbf{R}_{n-m} \mathbf{k}_n

This depends only on the relative position n-m. \square

This property is crucial for EEG decoding, as neural patterns should be compared based on their relative timing rather than absolute position within a window.

