A.4 Lyapunov Stability Proof for PID Control

The robotic manipulator dynamics are given by:

\mathbf{M}(\mathbf{q})\ddot{\mathbf{q}} + \mathbf{C}(\mathbf{q}, \dot{\mathbf{q}})\dot{\mathbf{q}} + \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{q}) = \boldsymbol{\tau}

where \mathbf{M}(\mathbf{q}) is the symmetric positive definite inertia matrix, \mathbf{C}(\mathbf{q}, \dot{\mathbf{q}}) is the Coriolis/centrifugal matrix, and \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{q}) is the gravity vector. A well-known property is that \dot{\mathbf{M}}(\mathbf{q}) - 2\mathbf{C}(\mathbf{q}, \dot{\mathbf{q}}) is skew-symmetric.

The PID control law with gravity compensation is:

\boldsymbol{\tau} = \mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} + \mathbf{K}_i \int \mathbf{e} \, dt + \mathbf{K}_d \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{q})

where \mathbf{e} = \mathbf{q}_d - \mathbf{q} is the tracking error.

Theorem A.4 (Global Asymptotic Stability). For constant desired joint angles \mathbf{q}_d, the closed-loop system with the above PID control law is globally asymptotically stable for \mathbf{K}_p, \mathbf{K}_i, \mathbf{K}_d > 0 (positive definite matrices).

Proof. Define the state vector \mathbf{x} = \begin{pmatrix} \int \mathbf{e} \, dt & \mathbf{e} & \dot{\mathbf{e}} \end{pmatrix}^\top. Consider the Lyapunov function candidate:

V(\mathbf{x}) = \frac{1}{2} \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \mathbf{M}(\mathbf{q}) \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \frac{1}{2} \mathbf{e}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} + \frac{1}{2} \left( \int \mathbf{e} \, dt \right)^\top \mathbf{K}_i \left( \int \mathbf{e} \, dt \right)

Taking the time derivative along the closed-loop trajectory:

\begin{aligned}
\dot{V} &= \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \mathbf{M}(\mathbf{q}) \ddot{\mathbf{e}} + \frac{1}{2} \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \dot{\mathbf{M}}(\mathbf{q}) \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \mathbf{e}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \left( \int \mathbf{e} \, dt \right)^\top \mathbf{K}_i \mathbf{e} \\
&= \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top (-\mathbf{C}(\mathbf{q}, \dot{\mathbf{q}})\dot{\mathbf{e}} - \mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} - \mathbf{K}_i \int \mathbf{e} \, dt - \mathbf{K}_d \dot{\mathbf{e}}) + \frac{1}{2} \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \dot{\mathbf{M}}(\mathbf{q}) \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \mathbf{e}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \left( \int \mathbf{e} \, dt \right)^\top \mathbf{K}_i \mathbf{e}
\end{aligned}

Using the skew-symmetry property \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top (\dot{\mathbf{M}} - 2\mathbf{C}) \dot{\mathbf{e}} = 0, the \mathbf{C} and \dot{\mathbf{M}} terms cancel:

\dot{V} = \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top (-\mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} - \mathbf{K}_i \int \mathbf{e} \, dt - \mathbf{K}_d \dot{\mathbf{e}}) + \mathbf{e}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \left( \int \mathbf{e} \, dt \right)^\top \mathbf{K}_i \mathbf{e}

Since \mathbf{K}_p and \mathbf{K}_i are symmetric, \mathbf{e}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \dot{\mathbf{e}} = \dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} and similarly for the integral term. Thus all terms except -\dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \mathbf{K}_d \dot{\mathbf{e}} cancel:

\dot{V} = -\dot{\mathbf{e}}^\top \mathbf{K}_d \dot{\mathbf{e}} \leq 0

Since \dot{V} \leq 0 and V is radially unbounded, the system is globally stable in the sense of Lyapunov. To prove asymptotic stability, we apply LaSalle's invariance principle. The set where \dot{V} = 0 is characterized by \dot{\mathbf{e}} = 0. On this invariant set, the closed-loop dynamics reduce to \mathbf{K}_p \mathbf{e} + \mathbf{K}_i \int \mathbf{e} \, dt = 0, which implies \mathbf{e} = 0 and \int \mathbf{e} \, dt = 0. The largest invariant set is the origin, thus global asymptotic stability follows. \square

