A.5 Adversarial Robustness via ABAT: Why Alignment Matters

Theorem A.5 (Consistency of Adversarial Attacks after EA). Let \mathcal{D}_s and \mathcal{D}_t be data distributions from two subjects with covariance matrices \mathbf{R}_s and \mathbf{R}_t. After Euclidean Alignment, both distributions have identity covariance. Then, an adversarial perturbation budget \epsilon defined in the aligned space corresponds to a consistent geometric perturbation across subjects.

Proof. For an original sample \mathbf{x} \sim \mathcal{D}_s, the aligned sample is \tilde{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{R}_s^{-1/2} \mathbf{x}. The adversarial perturbation \delta is added in the aligned space: \tilde{\mathbf{x}}_{adv} = \tilde{\mathbf{x}} + \delta with \|\delta\|_\infty \leq \epsilon. Mapping back to the original space, this corresponds to \mathbf{x}_{adv} = \mathbf{R}_s^{1/2} (\tilde{\mathbf{x}} + \delta) = \mathbf{x} + \mathbf{R}_s^{1/2} \delta. The perturbation in original space is \mathbf{R}_s^{1/2} \delta, which has magnitude dependent on the subject's covariance. After EA, all subjects share the same covariance \mathbf{I}, so the same \epsilon-ball has the same geometric meaning for all subjects, making the adversarial training consistent across the heterogeneous dataset. \square

